    {
      "text": "Which of the following statements about the instrument shown in the image given below is false?\n\n\n{{caption_text}}",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Used to measure the curvature of the cornea"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Assess corneal astigmatism."
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Depends on Purkinje image I."
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Measures intraocular pressure."
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 3,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer D - Measures <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1ba26fe8171692777190a867ec47c7\">intraocular</span> pressure.</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>The instrument shown in the image is a Keratometer used to assess the corneal <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4bd67d54f016927771850c953dadbc\">curvature</span> responsible for causing astigmatism. It is based on the size of the image formed by the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1ba6a9cfe11692777181950edd7a6d\">anterior</span> surface of the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4cc4d657841692777185555e1b982d\">cornea</span> i.e., purkinje image I.</li>\n\t<li>Intraocular pressure is measured by using a tonometer.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Keratometry </strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>An objective method for measuring the<strong> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4bd67d54f016927771850c953dadbc\">curvature</span> of the central <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4cc4d657841692777185555e1b982d\">cornea</span> (Option A ruled out) </strong>to estimate corneal astigmatism<strong> (Option B ruled out)</strong>.</li>\n\t<li><strong>Principle of Keratometer: </strong>Measures corneal <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4bd67d54f016927771850c953dadbc\">curvature</span> by <strong>analyzing the size of the image formed by the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1ba6a9cfe11692777181950edd7a6d\">anterior</span> corneal surface (Option C ruled out), utilizing visible doubling.</strong></li>\n\t<li><strong>Normal Keratometric Values: </strong>\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Average: <strong>45 D</strong></li>\n\t\t<li>Keratoconus >45 D</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n\t<li><strong>Types of Keratometers:</strong>\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Javal-Schiotz Model</li>\n\t\t<li>Bausch & Lomb Model</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<figure class=\"caption_element\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"\" data-author=\"Mass Communication Specialist 2nd Class Jonathen E. Davis\" data-hash=\"\" data-license=\"Open access\" data-source=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:US_Navy_101019-N-1531D-054_Air_Force_Master_Sgt._Breck_Downey_uses_a_auto-refractive_keratometer_to_determine_an_eye_prescription_during_a_Continui.jpg\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"488\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/content/FcCOrEpQJqdRT40CwT7H1747200439.png\" width=\"602\" />\n<figcaption>{{caption_text}}</figcaption>\n</figure>\n</div>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\">Auto <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cae831e44316927771973fa5e13fd7\">refractive</span> Keratometer </p>",
